Loreen

Lorine Zineb Nora Talhaoui, known profesionally as Loreen is a Swedish singer and songwriter. Born on 16th of October 1983, which makes her a libra, important to mention as she is known for her love of astrology.

Eurovision

Representing Sweden she has won the Eurovision Song Contest twice - in 2012 and 2023 - with the songs “Euphoria” and “Tattoo” respectively.

https://youtu.be/Pfo-8z86x80?feature=shared

https://youtu.be/BE2Fj0W4jP4?feature=shared

Fan base

She’s commonly referred to as “mother” who is “mothering”, within her fandom, as well as the Eurovision fandom.

Her nails are a well known statement and a popular attraction when it comes to her concerts, performance pieces, and the overall branding.

# These are packages I need for the analysis

Data preparation

There are some duplicated tracks and numerous versions of her greatest hit “Euphoria”, I decided to only leave the original track for each song therefore I’ve cleaned the data set accordingly.

# Filter out track names that include "Remix" or "Version" 
df <- df |> filter(!grepl("Remix|Version", track_name))
# Filter out album names that include "The Alternative Mixes"
df <- df |> filter(!grepl("The Alternative Mixes", album_name))
# For duplicates I made a new dataset as it will help in further analysis
df2 <- df |> distinct(track_name, .keep_all = TRUE)

Album analysis (speechiness, loudness and energy)

# Change album name from character to factor before plotting
df$album_name <- as.factor(df$album_name)
# Plot a boxplot
ggplot(df, aes(x=album_name, y=speechiness))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(x="Album name", y="Speechiness")

2013 has the highest medium - her ‘talkative’ year?

ggplot(df, aes(x=album_name, y=loudness))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(x="Album name", y="Loudness")

Her albums have gotten less loud over the years (2012, 2013, 2017).

ggplot(df, aes(x=album_name, y=energy))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(x="Album name", y="Energy")

Follows the same pattern as loudness which makes sense.

Is Loreen’s music good for dancing?

# Find top 3 songs for dancing But first remove records with the same track names
df2 |> slice_max(danceability, n=3) |> dplyr::select(track_name, album_name, album_release_year, danceability) |> knitr::kable(digits = 2)
track_name album_name album_release_year danceability
Do We Even Matter Heal (2013 Edition) 2013 0.63
See You Again Heal 2012 0.62
Sober Heal (2013 Edition) 2013 0.59
